<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="43" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="43">
Based on the ITS phylogeny, 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. difficilis" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="difficilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. difficilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. subtilis" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="subtilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. subtilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex with 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. bifurcata" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="bifurcata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. bifurcata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. cavernarum" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="cavernarum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. cavernarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. subtilis" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="subtilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. subtilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The involucrellum is usually longer than in 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. cavernarum" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="cavernarum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. cavernarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. subtilis" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="subtilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. subtilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Furthermore, the perithecia of 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. difficilis" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="difficilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. difficilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are, on average, less immersed, often only 1/4-1/2-immersed in rock. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pykaelae, Kantelinen &amp; Myllys" authorityYear="2020" class="Eurotiomycetes" family="Verrucariaceae" genus="Verrucaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Verrucaria bifurcata" order="Verrucariales" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="bifurcata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Verrucaria bifurcata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs in more immersed perithecia with the involucrellum appressed to the exciple. Nevertheless, 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. difficilis" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="difficilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. difficilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may not be identified with certainty without sequencing. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pykaelae &amp; Myllys" authorityYear="2020" class="Eurotiomycetes" family="Verrucariaceae" genus="Verrucaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Verrucaria difficilis" order="Verrucariales" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="difficilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Verrucaria difficilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also difficult to separate from 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. kuusamoensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="kuusamoensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. kuusamoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This species has slightly longer spores and the perithecia commonly leave deep pits in the rock.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="43">
A Genbank sequence 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Servit" authorityYear="1950" class="Eurotiomycetes" family="Verrucariaceae" genus="Verrucaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Verrucaria calkinsiana" order="Verrucariales" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="calkinsiana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Verrucaria calkinsiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Servít">Servit</normalizedToken>
(KT695332) has 98% similarity to 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. difficilis" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="difficilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. difficilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and it remains to be studied whether it is a closely-related species or possibly conspecific. Based on the morphology of the type specimen (PRM-857016!), 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. calkinsiana" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="calkinsiana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. calkinsiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not belong to the 
<taxonomicName genus="V." lsidName="V. subtilis" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="subtilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">V. subtilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex and the sequenced specimen is apparently misidentified.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
